                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName>
                                        <date>22<hi rend="sup">nd</hi> Mar 5609</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>Revd Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I hand you Letter 5 on the Union, being in
                                        continuation<lb/> of the exposition of the divine plan for
                                        the government of<lb/> man. Have the goodness to notify its
                                        receipt by you</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">The portion of the exposition now sent was rather
                                        difficult to<lb/> treat. I should like to have your opinion
                                        whether I have<lb/> succeeded or not in expounding the
                                        meaning of the Tree<lb/> of Life. The Tree of the Knowledge
                                        of Good &amp; Evil. The<lb/> sentences pronounced upon
                                                  <persName>Adam</persName> and
                                                  <persName>Eve</persName> and upon the<lb/> serpent
                                        &amp;c &amp;c At the conclusion of the letter I have
                                        inti=<lb/>=mated that my labours on the Union would cease
                                        for a<lb/> time; my reasons for which are there.—The meeting
                                        takes<lb/> place on the <date>11<hi rend="sup">th</hi>,
                                                  June</date>, the letter now sent will just be
                                        in<lb/> time to be published before, and as in my two
                                        letters 1 &amp; 2 I<lb/> have given my opinion on the
                                        principles on which to base the<lb/> Union and likewise on
                                        the mode on which the deliberations<lb/> of the meeting
                                        should be conducted, and you have very ably<lb/> pointed out
                                        some of the objects that might engage the<lb/> attention of
                                        the union when formed, there is plenty of matter<lb/> for
                                        the present occasion, for I thought and do still think that
                                        it<lb/> was sufficient to support in general terms what
                                        constitute the<lb/> duties obligatory on Israelites, and
                                        that the proposed meeting<lb/> would have nothing to do
                                        except to decide whether a Union</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>was expedient or not for fulfilling those duties and if it was<lb/>
                                        decided in the affirmative then to revert to steps for<lb/>
                                        inducing the congregations to take the matter into
                                        their<lb/> hands and found the Union, and it would belong to
                                        the<lb/> Body appointed to carry out its objects to promote
                                                  <add>?</add><lb/> to fulfill the duties. I cannot
                                        say I understand in what<lb/> light the proposed meeting is
                                        to be viewed. By the circular<lb/> and what some here say it
                                        would appear it is to form<lb/> the Union at once and
                                        proceed to legislate upon measures<lb/> still this does not
                                        appear possible if I am rightly informed<lb/> that no
                                        sending the delegates the congregation mean nothing<lb/> but
                                        that they should have representatives at a meeting to
                                        be<lb/> purely of a suggestive and <sic>advisary</sic>
                                        character and not at<lb/> all legislative. With the crude
                                        notions of some and the<lb/> small intelligence evinced by
                                        others how to handle a measure<lb/> so important as a union
                                        of the congregations, I shall regret<lb/> but certainly
                                        shall not be surprised that the whole prove<lb/> a failure I
                                        remain</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Revd Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Yrs. very truly</p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                                        <hi rend="indent(3)">
                                                  <persName role="author">A A. Lindo</persName>
                                        </hi>
                              </p>
                              <p>I have just discovered an error in the second line of the<lb/>
                                        concluding paragraph of my letter 2. page 612 of the<lb/>
                                        occident for <date>march</date>, the word “Spiritual” having
                                        been<lb/> substituted for “perpetual” which I will thank you
                                        to take<lb/> on early opportunity to notice. Yrs <persName
                                                  role="author">AAL</persName></p>
